Final_description: Counting was a difficult task in ancient Rome. The Arabic numerals 0,1,2,3,..., 9 were not yet in vogue. title: The solution to $x^3 = q can be approximated by computing the asymptotic formula $x_n + 1 = x_n - q. When the value of $|x.3 - q| is small enough, the calculation is stopped and the last calculated value is used as the approximate solution of q.

Final_description: There is a transformation operation for finite number sequences called the frequency-of-occurrence operation. The result of the transformation of the sequence $s = \{s_1, s_2,... s_n\}$, the result of the transformation is a sequence of numbers of the same length. The result is $c = \{c_1,c_2, ... , c_n\}$, where $c_i$ is the number of $s_i$ in the number sequence $s$. For example, if $s = \{3,4,1,5,9,2,6,5,3\}$, then $c = {2,1,1,2,1,1,1,1,2,2}$. Furthermore, by performing the frequency of occurrence operation on this sequence $c$, we obtain $p = \{4,5,5,4,5,5,5,5,4,4\}$. This number sequence is not changed by the frequency of occurrence operation. Such a sequence $p$ is called an immovable point of the sequence $s$. It is known that the fixed point of any sequence can be found by repeating the frequency of occurrence operation. The example below illustrates the procedure of the frequency-of-occurrence operation, where the first row is the sequence $s$, the second row is the sequence $c$, and the last row is the sequence $p$. The first element $c_1$ of sequence $c$ is 3 since there are 3 numbers equal to the first element of sequence $s$ ($s_1 = 2$), the second element $c_2 = 2$ since there are 2 numbers equal to the next element ($s_2 = 7$), etc. Count the numbers and find $c_i$. Create a program that takes a sequence length $n$ and a sequence $s$ and outputs a sequence $p$ of immovable points and the minimum number of frequency-of-occurrence operations performed to obtain $p$.
title: There is a transformation operation for finite number sequences called the frequency-of-occurrence operation. The result of the transformation is a sequence of numbers of the same length called c. The fixed point of any sequence can be found by repeating the frequency of occurrence operation.

The square taking method calculates the square of the initial value s when the number of digits of the random number to be generated is n, considers the number as a 2n-digit number (when the number of squared digits is not enough, as in the example below, it is supplemented with 0), and generates the first random number in the center of the square. Final_description: For a positive integer n, divide by 2 if n is even. If n is odd, multiply by 3 and add 1. Repeat this operation for any positive integer n, and the result will always be 1. It is known that there is no counterexample for very large numbers 3 × 253 = 27,021,597,764,222,976 or less using computers, but it has not been mathematically proven. Write a program that takes an integer n as input and outputs the number of times the operation is repeated until the result is 1. The integer n must be greater than or equal to 1 and must be less than or equal to 1000000 during the repetition of the above calculation. Final_description: Numbers obtained by multiplying 1 by 2, 3, or 5 several times (zero or more times) are called Hamming numbers. For example, 1 1 × 2 × 2 = 4 1 × 2 × 2 × 3 × 5 × 5 = 300 is a Hamming number, but 11, 13, 14, etc. are not. All Hamming numbers are divisible by a power of 60 (e.g., 54 is divisible by 603 = 21600), so they have long been known as convenient numbers for calculating times and other 60-decimal calculations. In addition, the pure temperament, one of the scales used for tuning musical instruments, is a sequence of numbers consisting of the Hamming numbers 24, 27, 30, 32, 36, 40, 45, and 48, which are the ratios of the frequencies of tones. Final_description: Alignment (sorting) algorithms for sorting data are fundamental to computer science. For example, sorting is the operation of "sorting the elements of an array of integer values in ascending order," as shown in the figure below. Many sorting algorithms have been devised, and one of the most fundamental algorithms is bubble sort. As an example, let us sort a given array of integer values in ascending order using bubble sort. In bubble sort, the array is divided into "sorted" and "unsorted" portions at each computation step. Initially, the entire array is the unsorted portion. Starting at the beginning of the unsorted portion, we compare the elements next to each other (green elements in the figure) and exchange them so that the larger value is to the right. If two values are equal, they are not exchanged. This process is repeated until the end of the unsorted portion (white elements in the figure). Finally, the tail is added to the sorted portion (blue element in the figure) to complete the step. This step is repeated until the length of the unsorted portion is 1. When the length of the unsorted portion reaches 1, the sorting process is complete. Now, create a program that takes an array of n numbers as input, uses the above bubble sort procedure to sort the numbers in ascending order from the beginning of the array, and outputs the number of times the array elements were exchanged.
title: Sorting algorithms for sorting data are fundamental to computer science. One of the most fundamental algorithms is bubble sort. In bubble sort, the array is divided into "sorted" and "unsorted" portions at each computation step. When the length of the unsorted portion reaches 1, the sorting process is complete.

title: Peter will make a program that converts sentences into a sequence of words with the number of letters in each word. It will be useful for remembering Pi, which used to be 3.1416, but now it's back to 3. 14. Peter and Dr. will work on it together.

Final_description: there are a number of ways to shuffle a deck of cards. hanafuda shuffling for japanese card game 'hanafuda' is one such example. the following is how to perform hanafuda shuffling. there is a deck of n cards. starting from the p-th card from the top of the deck, c cards are pulled out and put on the top of the deck, as shown in figure 1. this operation, called a cutting operation, is repeated. write a program that simulates hanafuda shuffling and answers which card will be finally placed on the top of the deck. figure 1: cutting operation
title: There are a number of ways to shuffle a deck of cards for Japanese card game 'hanafuda'. A program simulates hanafuda shuffling and answers which card will be placed on the top of the deck in the figure 1. It is possible to write a program that simulates this process.

Final_description: there is a rectangular room, covered with square tiles. each tile is colored either red or black. a man is standing on a black tile. from a tile, he can move to one of four adjacent tiles. but he can't move on red tiles, he can move only on black tiles. write a program to count the number of black tiles which he can reach by repeating the moves described above.
title: There is a rectangular room covered with square tiles. Each tile is colored either red or black. If a man is standing on a black tile from a tile, he can move to one of four adjacent tiles, but he can't move on red tiles. He can move only on black tiles.

Final_description: the international clown and pierrot competition (icpc), is one of the most distinguished and also the most popular events on earth in the show business. one of the unique features of this contest is the great number of judges that sometimes counts up to one hundred. the number of judges may differ from one contestant to another, because judges with any relationship whatsoever with a specific contestant are temporarily excluded for scoring his/her performance. basically, scores given to a contestant's performance by the judges are averaged to decide his/her score. to avoid letting judges with eccentric viewpoints too much influence the score, the highest and the lowest scores are set aside in this calculation. if the same highest score is marked by two or more judges, only one of them is ignored. the same is with the lowest score. the average, which may contain fractions, are truncated down to obtain final score as an integer. you are asked to write a program that computes the scores of performances, given the scores of all the judges, to speed up the event to be suited for a tv program.
title: The international clown and pierrot competition is one of the most distinguished and popular events on earth in the show business. There are many judges and scores are averaged to decide a contestant's score. The highest and the lowest scores are set aside in this calculation. The scores are truncated down to obtain the final score.

Final_description: one of the oddest traditions of the town of gameston may be that even the town mayor of the next term is chosen according to the result of a game. when the expiration of the term of the mayor approaches, at least three candidates, including the mayor of the time, play a game of pebbles, and the winner will be the next mayor. the rule of the game of pebbles is as follows. in what follows, n is the number of participating candidates. requisites a round table, a bowl, and plenty of pebbles. start of the game a number of pebbles are put into the bowl; the number is decided by the administration commission using some secret stochastic process. all the candidates, numbered from 0 to n-1 sit around the round table, in a counterclockwise order. initially, the bowl is handed to the serving mayor at the time, who is numbered 0. game steps when a candidate is handed the bowl and if any pebbles are in it, one pebble is taken out of the bowl and is kept, together with those already at hand, if any. if no pebbles are left in the bowl, the candidate puts all the kept pebbles, if any, into the bowl. then, in either case, the bowl is handed to the next candidate to the right. this step is repeated until the winner is decided. end of the game when a candidate takes the last pebble in the bowl, and no other candidates keep any pebbles, the game ends and that candidate with all the pebbles is the winner. a math teacher of gameston high, through his analysis, concluded that this game will always end within a finite number of steps, although the number of required steps can be very large.
title: The mayor of the town of gameston is chosen according to the result of a game of pebbles. At least three candidates, including the mayor, sit around a round table, in a counterclockwise order, and play the game. The winner is chosen when the last pebble in the bowl is taken out of the bowl and no other candidates keep any pebbled, and the winner is the one with all the remaining ones.

Final_description: you are given a marine area map that is a mesh of squares, each representing either a land or sea area. figure b-1 is an example of a map. figure b-1: a marine area map you can walk from a square land area to another if they are horizontally, vertically, or diagonally adjacent to each other on the map. two areas are on the same island if and only if you can walk from one to the other possibly through other land areas. the marine area on the map is surrounded by the sea and therefore you cannot go outside of the area on foot. you are requested to write a program that reads the map and counts the number of islands on it. for instance, the map in figure b-1 includes three islands.
title: A marine area map is a mesh of squares, each representing either a land or sea area. Two areas are on the same island if and only if you can walk from one to the other possibly through other land areas. The marine area on the map is surrounded by the sea and therefore you cannot go outside of the area on foot.

Final_description: the world should be finely balanced. positive vs. negative, light vs. shadow, and left vs. right brackets. your mission is to write a program that judges whether a string is balanced with respect to brackets so that we can observe the balance of the world. for every left round bracket (“(”), there is a corresponding right round bracket (“)”) in the following part of the string. for every left square bracket (“[”), there is a corresponding right square bracket (“]”) in the following part of the string. for every right bracket, there is a left bracket corresponding to it. correspondences of brackets have to be one to one, that is, a single bracket never corresponds to two or more brackets. for every pair of corresponding left and right brackets, the substring between them is balanced.
title: Your mission is to write a program that judges whether a string is balanced with respect to brackets so that we can observe the balance of the world. For every left round bracket there is a corresponding right round bracket in the following part of the string. for every pair of corresponding left and right brackets, the substring between them is balanced.

Final_description: the king of a little kingdom on a little island in the pacific ocean frequently has childish ideas. one day he said, “you shall make use of a message relaying game when you inform me of something.” in response to the king’s statement, six servants were selected as messengers whose names were mr. j, miss c, mr. e, mr. a, dr. p, and mr. m. they had to relay a message to the next messenger until the message got to the king. messages addressed to the king consist of digits (‘0’-‘9’) and alphabet characters (‘a’-‘z’, ‘a’-‘z’). capital and small letters are distinguished in messages. for example, “ke3e9aa” is a message. contrary to king’s expectations, he always received wrong messages, because each messenger changed messages a bit before passing them to the next messenger. since it irritated the king, he told you who are the minister of the science and technology agency of the kingdom, “we don’t want such a wrong message any more. you shall develop software to correct it!” in response to the king’s new statement, you analyzed the messengers’ mistakes with all technologies in the kingdom, and acquired the following features of mistakes of each messenger. a surprising point was that each messenger made the same mistake whenever relaying a message. the following facts were observed. mr. j rotates all characters of the message to the left by one. for example, he transforms “ab23d” to “b23da”. miss c rotates all characters of the message to the right by one. for example, she transforms “ab23d” to “dab23”. mr. e swaps the left half of the message with the right half. if the message has an odd number of characters, the middle one does not move. for example, he transforms “e3ac” to “ace3”, and “ab23d” to “3d2ab”. mr. a reverses the message. for example, he transforms “ab23d” to “d32ba”. dr. p increments by one all the digits in the message. if a digit is ‘9’, it becomes ‘0’. the alphabet characters do not change. for example, he transforms “ab23d” to “ab34d”, and “e9ac” to “e0ac”. mr. m decrements by one all the digits in the message. if a digit is ‘0’, it becomes ‘9’. the alphabet characters do not change. for example, he transforms “ab23d” to “ab12d”, and “e0ac” to “e9ac”. the software you must develop is to infer the original message from the final message, given the order of the messengers. for example, if the order of the messengers is a -> j -> m -> p and the message given to the king is “ab23d”, what is the original message? according to the features of the messengers’ mistakes, the sequence leading to the final message is as a result, the original message should be “32bad”.
title: The king of a little kingdom on a little island in the pacific ocean often has childish ideas. Six servants had to relay a message to the next messenger until the message got to the king. Each messenger made the same mistake whenever relaying a message. The minister of the science and technology agency of the kingdom will develop a software to correct the wrong messages.

Final_description: the sequence of n - 1 consecutive composite numbers (positive integers that are not prime and not equal to 1) lying between two successive prime numbers p and p + n is called a prime gap of length n. for example, (24, 25, 26, 27, 28) between 23 and 29 is a prime gap of length 6. your mission is to write a program to calculate, for a given positive integer k, the length of the prime gap that contains k. for convenience, the length is considered 0 in case no prime gap contains k.
title: The sequence of prime numbers lying between two successive prime numbers p and p + n is called a prime gap of length n. For example, (24, 25, 26, 27, 28) between 23 and 29 is a Prime Gap of length 6. For a positive integer k, the length of the prime gap that contains k is 0.

Final_description: let us consider sets of positive integers less than or equal to n. note that all elements of a set are different. also note that the order of elements doesn't matter, that is, both {3, 5, 9} and {5, 9, 3} mean the same set. specifying the number of set elements and their sum to be k and s, respectively, sets satisfying the conditions are limited. when n = 9, k = 3 and s = 23, {6, 8, 9} is the only such set. there may be more than one such set, in general, however. when n = 9, k = 3 and s = 22, both {5, 8, 9} and {6, 7, 9} are possible. you have to write a program that calculates the number of the sets that satisfy the given conditions.
title: Sets of positive integers less than or equal to n satisfy the conditions k and s are limited when n = 9, k = 3 and s = 23. There may be more than one such set in general, but it's possible to write a program that calculates the number of the sets that satisfy the given conditions.

Final_description: mammy decided to give taro his first shopping experience. mammy tells him to choose any two items he wants from those listed in the shopping catalogue, but taro cannot decide which two, as all the items look attractive. thus he plans to buy the pair of two items with the highest price sum, not exceeding the amount mammy allows. as getting two of the same item is boring, he wants two different items. you are asked to help taro select the two items. the price list for all of the items is given. among pairs of two items in the list, find the pair with the highest price sum not exceeding the allowed amount, and report the sum. taro is buying two items, not one, nor three, nor more. note that, two or more items in the list may be priced equally.
title: Mammy is giving taro his first shopping experience. Taro will buy the pair of two items with the highest price sum, not exceeding the amount mammy allows, as getting two of the same item is boring and he wants to buy two different items.

Final_description: we often compute the average as the first step in processing statistical data. yes, the average is a good tendency measure of data, but it is not always the best. in some cases, the average may hinder the understanding of the data. for example, consider the national income of a country. as the term income inequality suggests, a small number of people earn a good portion of the gross national income in many countries. in such cases, the average income computes much higher than the income of the vast majority. it is not appropriate to regard the average as the income of typical people. let us observe the above-mentioned phenomenon in some concrete data. incomes of n people, a1, ... , an, are given. you are asked to write a program that reports the number of people whose incomes are less than or equal to the average (a1 + ... + an) / n.
title: The average is a good tendency measure of data, but it is not always the best. In some cases, the average may hinder the understanding of the data. The average income is not the income of typical people, but of people whose incomes are less than or equal to the average.

Final_description: Stardate 1603-1867, people call that period the edo era. edo refers to the most advanced space navigation technology of the time, the enhanced driving operation, developed by dr.izy in 1603. You are a space adventurer, flying through space to explore different planets. During your adventures, you discover a very strange planet. On the planet, there were mysterious seven-colored gemstones everywhere. You thought of attempting a descent to the planet, but found that it was impossible due to a serious problem. The planet's air contains a poisonous element that can kill a human being instantly upon contact. So, you came up with the idea of using a robot to retrieve the gem. You stand by in the orbit of the planet. Then, you retrieve the gems by remotely controlling the descending robot. You remotely control the robot with a sequence of commands consisting of a "direction to move" and a "distance to move" pair. When the robot finds gems along its travel path (including the destination point), it retrieves all of them. Your task is to write a program that determines whether the robot was able to retrieve all the gems when it finishes executing all the given instructions. Note that the range over which the robot retrieves the mysterious gems is not very large. Therefore, the entire range of the robot's movement can be represented by a two-dimensional plane. The robot moves inside (including the boundary line) a square with (0,0) and (20,20) as the lower left and upper right corners, respectively. The robot always descends to the center of the range, i.e., at the coordinates (10,10). It is also guaranteed that all the gems are on a grid point other than the center.
title: During the period 1603-1867, people call that period the edo era. edo refers to the most advanced space navigation technology of the time, the enhanced driving operation, developed by dr.izy in 1603. You are a space adventurer, flying through space to explore different planets. On one planet, there were mysterious seven-colored gemstones everywhere. You control a robot to retrieve the gems by remotely controlling the descending robot.

Final_description: alice is trying to send a text message to miku on her cell phone. The only buttons on the phone that can be used for input are the number buttons. Therefore, he presses the number buttons several times to input text. The number buttons on the cell phone are assigned the next character, and button 0 is assigned the confirm button. In this cell phone, the user is required to press the confirm button whenever he/she finishes inputting a character. For example, if button 2, button 2, button 0 is pressed, the character changes from 'a' to 'b', and the confirm button is pressed at this point, so the character b is output. If the same number is inputted continuously, the changing character loops. That is, if button 2 is pressed five times and then button 0 is pressed, the character changes from 'a' → 'b' → 'c' → 'a' → 'b', at which point the confirm button is pressed and the character 'b' is output. It is possible to press the confirm button when no button is pressed, but in that case no character is output. Your job is to reproduce the message created by alice from the sequence of buttons pressed by alice.
title: Alice is trying to send a text message to miku on her cell phone. The only buttons on the phone that can be used for input are the number buttons. The number buttons are assigned the next character and the confirm button is assigned the confirmation button.

Final_description: Ken Marineblue is a space hunter who travels the entire galaxy in search of space coconut crabs. The space coconut crab is the largest crustacean in the universe and is said to grow to over 400 meters in length with its legs spread out to over 1,000 meters. Many people have already seen space crabs, but none have succeeded in catching them. Ken's long-term research has uncovered important facts about the ecology of the space coconut crab. Surprisingly, the space cocoon crab lives by moving back and forth between normal space and hyperspace, using what is equivalent to the latest warp technology called phase-transition navigation. He also discovered that it takes a long time for the space cocoon crab to warp out of hyperspace into normal space, and that it cannot move into hyperspace for a while after warping out. Ken finally decided to capture the space coconut crab. The strategy was as follows. First, he observes the energy of the space cocoon crab as it enters hyperspace from normal space. When this energy is denoted as e, the coordinates (x, y, z) at which the space cocoon crab warps out of hyperspace are known to satisfy the following conditions. x, y, z are all non-negative integers. x + y2 + z3 = e. Under the above conditions, the value of x + y + z is minimized. Although these conditions alone do not necessarily determine the coordinates uniquely, when the minimum value of x + y + z is m, it is certain that the coordinates to warp out lie on the plane x + y + z = m. Therefore, a barrier of sufficient size is placed on this plane. Then, the space coconut crab will warp out to the place where the barrier is placed. The space coconut crab affected by the barrier will be unable to move. The plan is to capture the space coconut crab by Weapon Breaker, a state-of-the-art spaceship operated by Ken. The barrier can only be put up once, so it cannot fail. Ken has decided to use the help of his calculator to accomplish his mission. Your task is to write a program to find the plane x + y + z = m on which the barrier should be placed given the energy of the space coconut crab's entry into hyperspace. Your program will be accepted when it outputs correct results for all of the test cases provided.
title: Ken Marineblue is a space hunter who travels the galaxy in search of space coconut crabs. The space coconut crab is the largest crustacean in the universe and is said to grow to over 400 meters in length with its legs spread out to over 1,000 meters. Ken's long-term research has uncovered important facts about the ecology of the space cocoon crab. It lives by moving back and forth between normal space and hyperspace using what is equivalent to the latest warp technology called phase-transition navigation. Ken has decided to use the help of his calculator to accomplish his mission.

Final_description: One day, a tomboyish and brave princess from a poor country broke down the wall of her room, escaped from the castle, and entered a gambling hall where horse races and other forms of gambling were being held. However, the princess, who had never gambled before, was very much defeated. The princess, who found this situation uninteresting, investigated how gambling was conducted. She discovered that the payout in such gambling was determined by a method called the pari-mutuel system. The pari-mutuel system is a calculation method used to determine the payout in competitive gambling. In this method, all bets are pooled, a certain percentage is deducted, and the winners are distributed an amount proportional to their bets. In the gambling game that the princess is currently into, participants buy 100 gold tickets before the game to predict which competitor will win, and if the result of the game matches the prediction, they are entitled to receive the prize money. Gold is the currency unit of the country. Your task is to write a program that calculates the payout per ticket based on the competition information provided as input. If the dividend calculated by the method described above is not a whole number, it must be rounded down to a whole number.
title: A princess from a poor country broke down the wall of her room and entered a gambling hall where horse races and other forms of gambling were being held. She discovered that the payout in such gambling was determined by a method called the pari-mutuel system. Your task is to write a program that calculates the payout per ticket based on the competition information provided as input.

Final_description: Professor Matsuzaki is a scientist who studies the truth of the universe. He believes that the truth of the universe can be expressed by a function consisting of two parameters, of which 42 is only one. Professor Matsuzaki believes that the truth of the universe can be expressed as a function of two parameters, of which 42 is only one. The function m(n, p) defined by Professor Matsuzaki represents the p-th number that appears when the entire set of numbers obtained by summing two prime numbers greater than n (or two identical numbers), ordered from the lowest to the highest. Here, there are numbers that can be expressed as two or more sums, but such numbers are arranged in the same number of combinations as the number of sums. As an example, consider the case n = 0. In this case, two of the prime numbers are chosen to be summed. Considering the smallest such sum, we know that 2 + 2 = 4, since we are allowed to choose the same number twice. That is, m(0, 1) = 4. The next smallest number is 2 + 3 = 5, so m(0, 2) = 5. In the same way, we see that the sequence of sums is 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 10, 12, 13, 14, 14, 16, .... .... That is, for example, m(0, 9) = 12. In the same way, for n = 10, we have to choose two of the prime numbers {11, 13, 17, 19, ...} The resulting sums, in decreasing order, are 22, 24, 26, 28, 30, 30, 32, .... ...}, the resulting sums are 22, 24, 26, 28, 30, 30, 32, ... Your task is to write a program that computes m(n, p) given n and p.
title: Professor Matsuzaki believes that the truth of the universe can be expressed by a function consisting of two parameters, of which 42 is only one. The function m(n, p) represents the p-th number that appears when the entire set of numbers obtained by summing two prime numbers greater than n (or two identical numbers), ordered from the lowest to the highest.

Final_description: as many of you know, we have two major calendar systems used in japan today. one of them is gregorian calendar which is widely used across the world. it is also known as “western calendar” in japan. the other calendar system is era-based calendar, or so-called “japanese calendar.” this system comes from ancient chinese systems. recently in japan it has been a common way to associate dates with the emperors. in the era-based system, we represent a year with an era name given at the time a new emperor assumes the throne. if the era name is “a”, the first regnal year will be “a 1”, the second year will be “a 2”, and so forth. since we have two different calendar systems, it is often needed to convert the date in one calendar system to the other. in this problem, you are asked to write a program that converts western year to era-based year, given a database that contains association between several western years and era-based years. for the simplicity, you can assume the following: a new era always begins on january 1st of the corresponding gregorian year. the first year of an era is described as 1. there is no year in which more than one era switch takes place. please note that, however, the database you will see may be incomplete. in other words, some era that existed in the history may be missing from your data. so you will also have to detect the cases where you cannot determine exactly which era the given year belongs to.
title: There are two calendar systems used in Japan: gregorian calendar and era-based calendar. It is often necessary to convert the date in one calendar system to the other. You are asked to write a program that converts western year to an era based year.

Final_description: icpc (international committee of privacy and confidence) is an organization with many members around the world, and as the name implies, it is a very icpc (international committee of privacy and confidence) is an organization with many members around the world, and as its name implies, it is an extremely privacy-oriented and secretive group. Members are required to keep personal information about other members strictly confidential, even though they may have access to it by necessity. As an account control manager (acm) of icpc, you must immediately identify the members whose information has been compromised and take strict action against them. Since you are an administrator with greater authority than the members, you are fully aware of who has been privy to whose personal information. Of course, no constituent can leak the personal information of a constituent he or she does not know. However, the perpetrator may not have leaked all the personal information he or she knows. From the list of the members whose personal information has been compromised, let's try to identify (if possible) which member compromised the personal information. By the way, the purpose of icpc's activities is a top secret and cannot be known even with the authority of the administrator.
title: ICP (international committee of privacy and confidence) is an organization with many members around the world. Members are required to keep personal information about other members strictly confidential. Account control manager of icpc must immediately identify the members whose information has been compromised and take strict action against them.

Final_description: You are a judge for the programming contest icpc. Today, the contest went off without a hitch, and all you had to do was output the results, when all of a sudden the system stopped!  You can't output the results! But don't worry. We have logs. You are a good programmer and once had a brilliant performance at icpc. So you decide to create a program that will determine each team's score from the system logs and output a team standings table. As input, you are given the number of teams, the number of problems, and the system logs. The simtem log consists of the following two types of records. Note that the above system log is a simplified version for this problem and differs from the system log seen in the production icpc. The team that solves more problems will be ranked higher If the problems solved are the same, the team with the lowest penalty will be ranked higher If the problems solved and the penalty are the same, the team with the lowest team number will be ranked higher Output a ranking list of the teams based on the contest information and the system logs provided by the input.
title: You are a judge for the programming contest icpc. Today's contest went off without a hitch. You had to create a program that will determine each team's score from the system logs and output a team standings table. The team that solves more problems will be ranked higher. If the problems solved and the penalty are the same, the team with the lowest number is ranked lower.

Final_description: Taro is an elementary school student who has just started learning kakezan. Somehow, he likes kakezan so much that whenever he sees a number, he wants to do it. He seems to like to do the following process on integers greater than or equal to 0. (If an integer n greater than or equal to 0 is a decimal integer, the process ends there. If an integer n greater than or equal to 10 in decimal representation has a break somewhere between the digits, it is possible to break it into two numbers (e.g., 2012-> 20,12). For such a possible cut, multiply the two numbers obtained and return to Step 1 with the largest one as the next n. (For details, see the following "Supplemental information on Step 2".) Taro likes this process, but he cannot predict how many times he has to repeat the operation of Step 2 for large numbers, and thinks that it may have to be done an infinite number of times. So, you, Taro's older brother and a college student, have asked him how many times this procedure 2 must be done for an integer n greater than or equal to 0. Your job is to find out, given q integers n1..nq greater than or equal to 0, how many times step 2 must be done for each integer before the process is completed. If you then need an infinite number of steps, output -1.
title: Taro has just started learning kakezan. He likes to do the following process on integers greater than or equal to 0. He can't predict how many times he has to repeat the operation of Step 2 for large numbers. Taro's older brother is a college student and wants to find out how many steps step 2 must be done for each integer before the process is completed.

Final_description: One room uses an electronic locking system that uses ic cards to open and close the locks. The system works as follows. When each user holds up his/her ic card to the door, the id of the ic card is passed to the system. If the system is registered with the id, it unlocks the door if it is locked, otherwise it locks the door, and a message is output respectively. If the id is not registered, the system outputs a message saying that it is not registered, and the door is not unlocked or locked. Now, the system currently has n ids (u1, u2, ......, un) registered and the door is locked. Suppose that an ic card is held over the door m times, and each id is t1, t2, ......, tm in that order. Find what message the system outputs at this time.
title: The room uses an electronic locking system that uses ic cards to open and close the locks. If an ic card is held over the door, the id of the card is passed to the system. If the system is registered with the id, it unlocks the door if it is locked, otherwise it locks the door.

Final_description: Heisei, the current era name, will end on April 30, 1991, and a new era name will begin on the following day. The day after the last day of Heisei will be May 1 of the first year of the new era. In the system developed by acm-icpc ob/og (japanese alumni group; jag), dates are stored in the database in the format "Heisei y y y m mo d day" using the Japanese calendar (a Japanese calendar in which years are expressed by the number of years following the year in which they occur). Since this storage format cannot be changed, jag decides to store the date in the database using the Japanese calendar, assuming that the era number will not be changed, and convert the date to the format using the correct era number when outputting the date. Your task is to write a program to convert the date stored in jag's database to a date using either Heisei or the new era number. Since the new era has not yet been announced, we will use "? since the new era has not yet been announced.
title: Heisei, the current era name, will end on April 30, 1991 and a new era name will begin on the following day. The day after the last day of Heisei will be May 1 of the first year of the new era. The new era number has not yet been announced.

Final_description: Gacho-kun has a favorite watch. One day, the long hand of the watch was removed and lost somewhere. However, Gacho-kun wants to continue to use the watch, so he wants to read the time using only the short hand. Output the time (hour h, minute m) for the information θ of the short hand. The clock is a so-called analog clock, with numbers from 1 to 12 equally spaced in ascending clockwise order.
title: Gacho-kun has a favorite watch. One day, the long hand of the watch was removed and lost somewhere. He wants to continue to use the watch, so he wants to read the time using only the short hand. The clock is a so-called analog clock with numbers from 1 to 12.

Final_description: n problems are proposed for an upcoming contest. problem i has an initial integer score of a_i points. m judges are about to vote for problems they like. each judge will choose exactly v problems, independently from the other judges, and increase the score of each chosen problem by 1. after all m judges cast their vote, the problems will be sorted in non-increasing order of score, and the first p problems will be chosen for the problemset. problems with the same score can be ordered arbitrarily, this order is decided by the chief judge. how many problems out of the given n have a chance to be chosen for the problemset?
title: N problems are proposed for an upcoming contest. Each judge will vote for one of them and increase the score of each chosen problem by 1. The problems will be sorted in non-increasing order of score and the first p problems chosen for the problemset will be chosen.

Final_description: let us consider a grid of squares with n rows and n columns. you want to put some domino pieces on this grid. each domino piece covers two squares that have a common side. each square can be covered by at most one piece. for each row of the grid, let's define its quality as the number of domino pieces that cover at least one square in this row. we define the quality of each column similarly. find a way to put at least one domino piece on the grid so that the quality of every row is equal to the quality of every column, or determine that such a placement doesn't exist.
title: If you want to put domino pieces on a grid with n rows and n columns, you need to find a way to put at least one domino piece on the grid so that the quality of every row is equal to that of the other rows and columns.

Final_description: takahashi is solving quizzes. he has easily solved all but the last one. the last quiz has three choices: 1, 2, and 3. with his supernatural power, takahashi has found out that the choices a and b are both wrong. print the correct choice for this problem.
title: Takahashi is solving quizzes. He has easily solved all but the last one. Takahashi has found out that the choices a and b are both wrong and he has to print the correct choice for this problem. The last quiz has three choices: 1, 2, and 3.

Final_description: given are strings s and t of length n each, both consisting of lowercase english letters. let us form a new string by alternating the characters of s and the characters of t, as follows: the first character of s, the first character of t, the second character of s, the second character of t, ..., the n-th character of s, the n-th character of t. print this new string.
title: There are strings s and t of length n each, both consisting of lowercase english letters. Let's form a new string by alternating the characters of s and the characters from t to form the new string. print this new string as follows: first character of s, the first character from t, the second character from s, ..., the n-th character of t.

Final_description: takahashi is organizing a party. at the party, each guest will receive one or more snack pieces. takahashi predicts that the number of guests at this party will be a or b. find the minimum number of pieces that can be evenly distributed to the guests in both of the cases predicted. we assume that a piece cannot be divided and distributed to multiple guests.
title: Takahashi is organizing a party where each guest will receive one or more snack pieces. Takahashi predicts that the number of guests at the party will be a or b. Find the minimum number of pieces that can be evenly distributed to the guests in both of the cases.

Final_description: we have n bricks arranged in a row from left to right. the i-th brick from the left (1 \leq i \leq n) has an integer a_i written on it. among them, you can break at most n-1 bricks of your choice. let us say there are k bricks remaining. snuke will be satisfied if, for each integer i (1 \leq i \leq k), the i-th of those brick from the left has the integer i written on it. find the minimum number of bricks you need to break to satisfy snuke's desire. if his desire is unsatisfiable, print -1 instead.
title: If there are n bricks arranged in a row from left to right, the i-th brick from the left has an integer a_i written on it. If there are k bricks left, for each integer i (1 \leq i - k), find the minimum number of bricks you need to break to satisfy snuke's desire.

Final_description: for an integer n not less than 0, let us define f(n) as follows: f(n) = 1 (if n < 2) f(n) = n f(n-2) (if n \geq 2) given is an integer n. find the number of trailing zeros in the decimal notation of f(n).
title: For an integer n not less than 0, let us define f(n) as follows: f( n) = 1 (if n < 2) or n - 2, and find the number of trailing zeros in the decimal notation of f (n).

Final_description: we have a tree with n vertices. the i-th edge connects vertex a_i and b_i bidirectionally. takahashi is standing at vertex u, and aoki is standing at vertex v. now, they will play a game of tag as follows: 1. if takahashi and aoki are standing at the same vertex, the game ends. otherwise, takahashi moves to a vertex of his choice that is adjacent to his current vertex. 2. if takahashi and aoki are standing at the same vertex, the game ends. otherwise, aoki moves to a vertex of his choice that is adjacent to his current vertex. 3. go back to step 1. takahashi performs his moves so that the game ends as late as possible, while aoki performs his moves so that the game ends as early as possible. find the number of moves aoki will perform before the end of the game if both takahashi and aoki know each other's position and strategy. it can be proved that the game is bound to end.
title: Takahashi and aoki are playing a game of tag. If they are standing at the same vertices, the game ends, otherwise, they move to different vertices. If both players know each other's position and strategy, it can be proved that the game is bound to end.

Final_description: given are three integers a_1, a_2, and a_3. if a_1+a_2+a_3 is greater than or equal to 22, print bust; otherwise, print win.
title: There are three integers a_1, a_2, and a_3. If one of them is greater than or equal to 22, print bust. If it's not, print win. Otherwise it's equal to or less than 22.

Final_description: takahashi loves palindromes. non-palindromic strings are unacceptable to him. each time he hugs a string, he can change one of its characters to any character of his choice. given is a string s. find the minimum number of hugs needed to make s palindromic.
title: Takahashi loves palindromes. Non-palindromic strings are unacceptable to Takahashi. He can change one of the strings characters to any character of his choice each time he hugs a string. He finds the minimum number of hugs needed to make s palindrome.

Final_description: there are n people numbered 1 to n. each of them is either an honest person whose testimonies are always correct or an unkind person whose testimonies may be correct or not. person i gives a_i testimonies. the j-th testimony by person i is represented by two integers x_{ij} and y_{ij}. if y_{ij} = 1, the testimony says person x_{ij} is honest; if y_{ij} = 0, it says person x_{ij} is unkind. how many honest persons can be among those n people at most?
title: There are n people numbered 1 to n. Each of them is either an honest person whose testimonies are always correct or an unkind person. The j-th testimony by person i is represented by two integers x and y. If x = 1, the testimony says person x is honest; if y = 0, it says person y is unkind.

Final_description: we have n integers. the i-th integer is a_i. find \sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\sum_{j=i+1}^{n} (a_i \mbox{ xor } a_j), modulo (10^9+7). when a \mbox{ xor } b is written in base two, the digit in the 2^k's place (k \geq 0) is 1 if either a or b, but not both, has 1 in the 2^k's place, and 0 otherwise. for example, 3 \mbox{ xor } 5 = 6. (in base two: 011 \mbox{ xor } 101 = 110.)
title: The i-th integer is a_i. When a is written in base two, the digit in the 2^k's place is 1 if either a or b has 1 in it, and 0 otherwise. 011 \mbox{ xor } 101 = 110.

Final_description: in this problem, a date is written as y-m-d. for example, 2019-11-30 means november 30, 2019. integers m_1, d_1, m_2, and d_2 will be given as input. it is known that the date 2019-m_2-d_2 follows 2019-m_1-d_1. determine whether the date 2019-m_1-d_1 is the last day of a month.
title: In this problem, a date is written as y-m-d. integers m_1, d_1 and m_2 will be used to determine whether the date 2019-m_1-d_1 is the last day of a month or not.

Final_description: takahashi bought a piece of apple pie at abc confiserie. according to his memory, he paid n yen (the currency of japan) for it. the consumption tax rate for foods in this shop is 8 percent. that is, to buy an apple pie priced at x yen before tax, you have to pay x \times 1.08 yen (rounded down to the nearest integer). takahashi forgot the price of his apple pie before tax, x, and wants to know it again. write a program that takes n as input and finds x. we assume x is an integer. if there are multiple possible values for x, find any one of them. also, takahashi's memory of n, the amount he paid, may be incorrect. if no value could be x, report that fact.
title: Takahashi bought an apple pie at abc confiserie. He paid n yen for it. The consumption tax rate for foods in this shop is 8 percent. Takahashi forgot the price of his apple pie before tax, x, and wants to know it again.

Final_description: atcoder mart sells 1000000 of each of the six items below: riceballs, priced at 100 yen (the currency of japan) each sandwiches, priced at 101 yen each cookies, priced at 102 yen each cakes, priced at 103 yen each candies, priced at 104 yen each computers, priced at 105 yen each takahashi wants to buy some of them that cost exactly x yen in total. determine whether this is possible. (ignore consumption tax.)
title: Atcoder mart sells 1000000 of each of the six items below. Takahashi wants to buy some of them that cost exactly x yen in total to determine if it's possible to do so.    (ignore consumption tax).   ...

Final_description: atcoder inc. has decided to lock the door of its office with a 3-digit pin code. the company has an n-digit lucky number, s. takahashi, the president, will erase n-3 digits from s and concatenate the remaining 3 digits without changing the order to set the pin code. how many different pin codes can he set this way? both the lucky number and the pin code may begin with a 0.
title: Atcoder inc. has decided to lock the door of its office with a 3-digit pin code. The company has an n-digit lucky number, s. Takahashi, the president, will erase n-3 digits from s and concatenate the remaining 3 digits.

Final_description: n people are standing in a queue, numbered 1, 2, 3, ..., n from front to back. each person wears a hat, which is red, blue, or green. the person numbered i says: "in front of me, exactly a_i people are wearing hats with the same color as mine." assuming that all these statements are correct, find the number of possible combinations of colors of the n people's hats. since the count can be enormous, compute it modulo 1000000007.
title: N people are standing in a queue, numbered 1, 2, 3, ..., n from front to back. Each person wears a hat, which is red, blue, or green. In front of i says: "in front of me, exactly a_i people are wearing hats with the same color as mine".

Final_description: takahashi and aoki are training for long-distance races in an infinitely long straight course running from west to east. they start simultaneously at the same point and moves as follows towards the east: takahashi runs a_1 meters per minute for the first t_1 minutes, then runs at a_2 meters per minute for the subsequent t_2 minutes, and alternates between these two modes forever. aoki runs b_1 meters per minute for the first t_1 minutes, then runs at b_2 meters per minute for the subsequent t_2 minutes, and alternates between these two modes forever. how many times will takahashi and aoki meet each other, that is, come to the same point? we do not count the start of the run. if they meet infinitely many times, report that fact.
title: Takahashi and aoki are training for long-distance races in an infinitely long straight course running from west to east. They start at the same point and move as follows towards the east. Takahashi runs a_1 meters per minute for the first t_1 minutes, then runs at a_2 meters per second for the subsequent t_2 minutes, and alternates between these two modes forever.

Final_description: given is a string s representing the day of the week today. s is sun, mon, tue, wed, thu, fri, or sat, for sunday, monday, tuesday, wednesday, thursday, friday, and saturday, respectively. after how many days is the next sunday (tomorrow or later)?
title: The string s represents the day of the week today and after that the next sunday (tomorrow or later) after that is the next Sunday (today or tomorrow) The number s is sun, mon, tue, wed, thu, friday, or sat.

Final_description: we have a string s consisting of uppercase english letters. additionally, an integer n will be given. shift each character of s by n in alphabetical order (see below), and print the resulting string. we assume that a follows z. for example, shifting a by 2 results in c (a \to b \to c), and shifting y by 3 results in b (y \to z \to a \to b).
title: Shift each character of s by n in alphabetical order and print the resulting string s. For example, shifting a by 2 results in c, shifting y by 3 results in b, and shifting z by 3 makes z follow z and a follows a.

Final_description: given is a tree g with n vertices. the vertices are numbered 1 through n, and the i-th edge connects vertex a_i and vertex b_i. consider painting the edges in g with some number of colors. we want to paint them so that, for each vertex, the colors of the edges incident to that vertex are all different. among the colorings satisfying the condition above, construct one that uses the minimum number of colors.
title: In a tree g with n vertices, the i-th edge connects vertices a_i and b_i. To paint the edges in g with the minimum number of colors, for each of the vertices the colors of the edges incident to that vertices are all different.

Final_description: takahashi is playing a board game called sugoroku. on the board, there are n + 1 squares numbered 0 to n. takahashi starts at square 0, and he has to stop exactly at square n to win the game. the game uses a roulette with the m numbers from 1 to m. in each turn, takahashi spins the roulette. if the number x comes up when he is at square s, he moves to square s+x. if this makes him go beyond square n, he loses the game. additionally, some of the squares are game over squares. he also loses the game if he stops at one of those squares. you are given a string s of length n + 1, representing which squares are game over squares. for each i (0 \leq i \leq n), square i is a game over square if s[i] = 1 and not if s[i] = 0. find the sequence of numbers coming up in the roulette in which takahashi can win the game in the fewest number of turns possible. if there are multiple such sequences, find the lexicographically smallest such sequence. if takahashi cannot win the game, print -1.
title: Takahashi is playing a board game called sugoroku. He starts at square 0 and has to stop exactly at square n to win the game. The game uses a roulette with the m numbers from 1 to m in each turn. If Takahashi can't win, print -1.

Final_description: we held two competitions: coding contest and robot maneuver. in each competition, the contestants taking the 3-rd, 2-nd, and 1-st places receive 100000, 200000, and 300000 yen (the currency of japan), respectively. furthermore, a contestant taking the first place in both competitions receives an additional 400000 yen. disco-kun took the x-th place in coding contest and the y-th place in robot maneuver. find the total amount of money he earned.
title: disco-kun took the x-th place in coding contest and the y-tenth place in robot maneuver. He earned 400,000 yen in total in both competitions, which is the equivalent of 100,000, 200, and 300,000 Japanese yen.

Final_description: takahashi, who works at disco, is standing before an iron bar. the bar has n-1 notches, which divide the bar into n sections. the i-th section from the left has a length of a_i millimeters. takahashi wanted to choose a notch and cut the bar at that point into two parts with the same length. however, this may not be possible as is, so he will do the following operations some number of times before he does the cut: choose one section and expand it, increasing its length by 1 millimeter. doing this operation once costs 1 yen (the currency of japan). choose one section of length at least 2 millimeters and shrink it, decreasing its length by 1 millimeter. doing this operation once costs 1 yen. find the minimum amount of money needed before cutting the bar into two parts with the same length.
title: Takahashi works at disco. Takahashi will do the following operations some number of times before cutting an iron bar into two parts with the same length: choose one section and expand it, increase its length by 1 millimeter, shrink it by 1 mm, and cut it in half.

Final_description: chokudai made a rectangular cake for contestants in ddcc 2020 finals. the cake has h - 1 horizontal notches and w - 1 vertical notches, which divide the cake into h \times w equal sections. k of these sections has a strawberry on top of each of them. the positions of the strawberries are given to you as h \times w characters s_{i, j} (1 \leq i \leq h, 1 \leq j \leq w). if s_{i, j} is #, the section at the i-th row from the top and the j-th column from the left contains a strawberry; if s_{i, j} is ., the section does not contain one. there are exactly k occurrences of #s. takahashi wants to cut this cake into k pieces and serve them to the contestants. each of these pieces must satisfy the following conditions: has a rectangular shape. contains exactly one strawberry. one possible way to cut the cake is shown below: find one way to cut the cake and satisfy the condition. we can show that this is always possible, regardless of the number and positions of the strawberries.
title: Chokudai made a rectangular cake for contestants in the DCC 2020 finals. Takahashi wants to cut the cake into k pieces and serve them to the contestants. Each of the k pieces must satisfy the following conditions: has a rectangular shape, contains exactly one strawberry, and is cut in a certain way.

Final_description: n programmers are going to participate in the preliminary stage of ddcc 20xx. due to the size of the venue, however, at most 9 contestants can participate in the finals. the preliminary stage consists of several rounds, which will take place as follows: all the n contestants will participate in the first round. the organizer will choose two consecutive digits in the decimal notation of x, and replace them with the sum of these digits. the number resulted will be the number of contestants advancing to the next round. for example, when x = 2378, the number of contestants advancing to the next round will be 578 (if 2 and 3 are chosen), 2108 (if 3 and 7 are chosen), or 2315 (if 7 and 8 are chosen). when x = 100, the number of contestants advancing to the next round will be 10, no matter which two digits are chosen. the preliminary stage ends when 9 or fewer contestants remain. ringo, the chief organizer, wants to hold as many rounds as possible. find the maximum possible number of rounds in the preliminary stage. since the number of contestants, n, can be enormous, it is given to you as two integer sequences d_1, \ldots, d_m and c_1, \ldots, c_m, which means the following: the decimal notation of n consists of c_1 + c_2 + \ldots + c_m digits, whose first c_1 digits are all d_1, the following c_2 digits are all d_2, \ldots, and the last c_m digits are all d_m.
title: N programmers are going to participate in the preliminary stage of ddcc 20xx. At most 9 contestants can participate in finals. Preliminary stage consists of several rounds. The organizer will choose two consecutive digits in the decimal notation of x and the number of contestants advancing to the next round will be the sum of them.

Final_description: given is an integer r. how many times is the area of a circle of radius r larger than the area of a circle of radius 1? it can be proved that the answer is always an integer under the constraints given.
title: The area of a circle of radius r is always an integer under the constraints given, so it can be proved that the answer is always the same for all circles of radius 1 and radius r. The answer to the question is always a positive integer, as it is always true.

Final_description: given are a positive integer n and a string s of length n consisting of lowercase english letters. determine whether the string is a concatenation of two copies of some string. that is, determine whether there is a string t such that s = t + t.
title: Given a positive integer n and a string s of length n consisting of lowercase english letters, determine whether the string is a concatenation of two copies of some string, and if there is a string t such that s = t + t, then the string s is concatenated.

Final_description: there are n towns in a coordinate plane. town i is located at coordinates (x_i, y_i). the distance between town i and town j is \sqrt{\left(x_i-x_j\right)^2+\left(y_i-y_j\right)^2}. there are n! possible paths to visit all of these towns once. let the length of a path be the distance covered when we start at the first town in the path, visit the second, third, \dots, towns, and arrive at the last town (assume that we travel in a straight line from a town to another). compute the average length of these n! paths.
title: There are n towns in a coordinate plane. There are n! possible paths to visit all of these towns once. The average length of these paths is the distance covered when we start at the first town in the path, visit the second, third, and fourth towns, and arrive at the last town.

Final_description: there is a knight - the chess piece - at the origin (0, 0) of a two-dimensional grid. when the knight is at the square (i, j), it can be moved to either (i+1,j+2) or (i+2, j+1). in how many ways can the knight reach the square (x, y)? find the number of ways modulo 10^9 + 7.
title: There is a knight - the chess piece - at the origin (0, 0) of a two-dimensional grid. When the knight is at the square (i, j), it can be moved to either (i+1,j+2 or (i-2, j+1). The number of ways the knight can reach the square is modulo 10^9 + 7.

Final_description: takahashi is at an all-you-can-eat restaurant. the restaurant offers n kinds of dishes. it takes a_i minutes to eat the i-th dish, whose deliciousness is b_i. the restaurant has the following rules: you can only order one dish at a time. the dish ordered will be immediately served and ready to eat. you cannot order the same kind of dish more than once. until you finish eating the dish already served, you cannot order a new dish. after t-0.5 minutes from the first order, you can no longer place a new order, but you can continue eating the dish already served. let takahashi's happiness be the sum of the deliciousness of the dishes he eats in this restaurant. what is the maximum possible happiness achieved by making optimal choices?
title: Takahashi is at an all-you-can-eat restaurant where he can only order one dish at a time. The dish ordered will be immediately served and ready to eat. After 0.5 minutes from the first order, you can no longer place a new order, but can continue eating the dish already served.

Final_description: how many ways are there to choose two distinct positive integers totaling n, disregarding the order?
title: There are two distinct positive integers totaling n disregarding the order. How many ways are there to choose one of them disregarding order?    n n n  n. n n.  n . n n is a positive integer with n differentiating n.

Final_description: given is an integer sequence d_1,...,d_n of n elements. find the number, modulo 998244353, of trees with n vertices numbered 1 to n that satisfy the following condition: for every integer i from 1 to n, the distance between vertex 1 and vertex i is d_i.
title: The number of trees with n vertices numbered 1 to n that satisfy the following condition is 998244353. For every integer i from 1 to i, the distance between vertices 1 and i is d_i, and the number of vertices with 1-n vertices is 1.

Final_description: we have n points numbered 1 to n arranged in a line in this order. takahashi decides to make an undirected graph, using these points as the vertices. in the beginning, the graph has no edge. takahashi will do m operations to add edges in this graph. the i-th operation is as follows: the operation uses integers l_i and r_i between 1 and n (inclusive), and a positive integer c_i. for every pair of integers (s, t) such that l_i \leq s < t \leq r_i, add an edge of length c_i between vertex s and vertex t. the integers l_1, ..., l_m, r_1, ..., r_m, c_1, ..., c_m are all given as input. takahashi wants to solve the shortest path problem in the final graph obtained. find the length of the shortest path from vertex 1 to vertex n in the final graph.
title: Takahashi wants to solve the shortest path problem in the final graph obtained. He uses the integers l_1, ..., l_m, r_1 and r_m to add an edge of length c_i between the vertices s and t.

Final_description: given is a string s of length n-1. each character in s is < or >. a sequence of n non-negative integers, a_1,a_2,\cdots,a_n, is said to be good when the following condition is satisfied for all i (1 \leq i \leq n-1): if s_i= <: a_i<a_{i+1} if s_i= >: a_i>a_{i+1} find the minimum possible sum of the elements of a good sequence of n non-negative integers.
title: A good sequence of n non-negative integers is said to be good when the following condition is satisfied for all i (1 \leq i - n-1): if s_i= <: a_i<a_i+1, and if s-i = > a-i, then the minimum possible sum of elements of the elements of a good sequence.

Final_description: having learned the multiplication table, takahashi can multiply two integers between 1 and 9 (inclusive) together. he cannot do any other calculation. given are two integers a and b. if takahashi can calculate a \times b, print the result; if he cannot, print -1 instead.
title: After learning the multiplication table Takahashi can multiply two integers between 1 and 9 (inclusive) together, but he cannot do any other calculation given are two integers a and b. If he can calculate a \times b, print the result; if he cannot, print -1 instead.

Final_description: having learned the multiplication table, takahashi can multiply two integers between 1 and 9 (inclusive) together. given an integer n, determine whether n can be represented as the product of two integers between 1 and 9. if it can, print yes; if it cannot, print no.
title: After learning the multiplication table Takahashi can multiply two integers between 1 and 9 (inclusive) together. given an integer n, determine whether n can be represented as the product of two integers. if it can be, print yes. If it cannot, print no.

Final_description: takahashi is standing on a multiplication table with infinitely many rows and columns. the square (i,j) contains the integer i \times j. initially, takahashi is standing at (1,1). in one move, he can move from (i,j) to either (i+1,j) or (i,j+1). given an integer n, find the minimum number of moves needed to reach a square that contains n.
title: Takahashi is standing on a multiplication table with infinitely many rows and columns. In one move he can move from (i,j) to either (i+1,j), or (i-j+1). Given an integer n, find the minimum number of moves needed to reach a square that contains n.

Final_description: takahashi has a water bottle with the shape of a rectangular prism whose base is a square of side a~\mathrm{cm} and whose height is b~\mathrm{cm}. (the thickness of the bottle can be ignored.) we will pour x~\mathrm{cm}^3 of water into the bottle, and gradually tilt the bottle around one of the sides of the base. when will the water be spilled? more formally, find the maximum angle in which we can tilt the bottle without spilling any water.
title: Takahashi has a water bottle with the shape of a rectangular prism whose base is a square of side a and whose height is b. When pouring water into the bottle and tilting the bottle around one of the sides, when will the water be spilled? Find the maximum angle in which we can tilt the bottle without spilling any water.

Final_description: takahashi will take part in an eating contest. teams of n members will compete in this contest, and takahashi's team consists of n players numbered 1 through n from youngest to oldest. the consumption coefficient of member i is a_i. in the contest, n foods numbered 1 through n will be presented, and the difficulty of food i is f_i. the details of the contest are as follows: a team should assign one member to each food, and should not assign the same member to multiple foods. it will take x \times y seconds for a member to finish the food, where x is the consumption coefficient of the member and y is the difficulty of the dish. the score of a team is the longest time it takes for an individual member to finish the food. before the contest, takahashi's team decided to do some training. in one set of training, a member can reduce his/her consumption coefficient by 1, as long as it does not go below 0. however, for financial reasons, the n members can do at most k sets of training in total. what is the minimum possible score of the team, achieved by choosing the amounts of members' training and allocating the dishes optimally?
title: Takahashi will take part in an eating contest. His team consists of n players numbered 1 through n from youngest to oldest. They will eat n foods from 1 to n. The difficulty of food i is f_i. The score of a team is the longest time it takes for an individual member to finish the food.

Final_description: the window of takahashi's room has a width of a. there are two curtains hung over the window, each of which has a horizontal length of b. (vertically, the curtains are long enough to cover the whole window.) we will close the window so as to minimize the total horizontal length of the uncovered part of the window. find the total horizontal length of the uncovered parts of the window then.
title: The window of Takahashi's room has a width of a. There are two curtains hung over the window, each of which has a horizontal length of b. We will close the window so as to minimize the total length of the uncovered parts of the window.
